   <mods:abstract>I argue that the dividing of values into epistemic and non-epistemic is not a productive way to understand and judge the influence of values in science. A better approach is to consider what is motivating a value and what justifies using it in a particular context. By reframing our assessment of values this way, we can better recognize epistemic contributions from diverse values. I further argue that when a value improves the empirical adequacy of a hypothesis or theory, the use of that value is epistemically justified in that context. To illustrate this point, I offer an example where the value of egalitarianism, which is widely considered to be a "non-epistemic value," improved the empirical adequacy of a neuroscientific hypothesis, rendering the value epistemically justified in that context. Ultimately, I hope to make plausible the epistemic advantage of using that which has traditionally been relegated to the category of the non-epistemicâ€”morally sound values.</mods:abstract>
